Subject: [PATCH] webgpu: propagate combined-sampler split through call chains

split_combined_samplers() rewrites GLSL combined image-samplers (sampler2D)
into WebGPU's required separate texture + sampler. A function that receives a
combined sampler as a parameter gets that parameter retyped to a plain image
pointer, and its combined loads are redirected to the split image/sampler pair.

The pass only started that rewrite for functions called with a combined GLOBAL
variable, so it missed wrapper chains: main -> wrapper(global sampler) -> leaf
(wrapper's parameter). The wrapper's parameter was split to ptr(Image) but the
leaf it forwarded to kept ptr(SampledImage), so the forwarded call became
invalid SPIR-V (OpFunctionCall argument type does not match the callee's
parameter type). Tint rejects the module and the shader silently fails to
translate. Godot's tonemap bicubic-glow path (texture2D_bicubic) and taa_resolve
hit exactly this.

Fix: after seeding the split from global-variable call sites, iterate to a
fixpoint, following every combined value forwarded through a parameter and
splitting each callee the same way, mapping its parameter back to the same
underlying global sampler so the in-function sampler load still resolves. The
existing type / parameter / load rewrite then covers the whole chain unchanged.

Verified offline with a native tint_convert_cli over all 182 engine shaders:
tonemap bicubic (x2) and taa_resolve now produce SPIR-V that passes SPIRV-Tools
validation and translates to correct WGSL (separate texture_2d + sampler with
the expected doubled bindings; textureSampleLevel wired to the split pair).
Result: 177 of 182 translate (was 174); 0 crash; the 5 remaining failures are
unrelated fundamental WGSL limits (subpass input_attachment, storage-texture
format inference, vertex-stage read_write storage, vertex @builtin(position)).

diff --git a/drivers/webgpu/spirv_preprocess.cpp b/drivers/webgpu/spirv_preprocess.cpp
--- a/drivers/webgpu/spirv_preprocess.cpp
+++ b/drivers/webgpu/spirv_preprocess.cpp
@@ -924,6 +924,15 @@
 	// func_type_id -> list of param_type_ids (from OpTypeFunction).
 	HashMap<uint32_t, Vector<uint32_t>> func_type_params;
 
+	// Every OpFunctionCall as (callee, [arg_ids...]). Needed for the transitive
+	// split-propagation fixpoint below (a combined sampler forwarded through a
+	// chain of wrapper functions).
+	struct CallRecord {
+		uint32_t func_id;
+		Vector<uint32_t> args;
+	};
+	Vector<CallRecord> all_calls;
+
 	// First scan: collect OpTypeFunction definitions.
 	{
 		uint32_t pos2 = 5;
@@ -990,13 +999,17 @@
 				case OP_FUNCTION_CALL: { // OpFunctionCall
 					if (wc2 >= 4) {
 						uint32_t func_id = read_word(data, len, pos2 + 3);
+						CallRecord rec;
+						rec.func_id = func_id;
 						for (uint32_t arg_idx = 0; arg_idx < wc2 - 4; arg_idx++) {
 							uint32_t arg_id = read_word(data, len, pos2 + 4 + arg_idx);
+							rec.args.push_back(arg_id);
 							if (combined_vars.has(arg_id)) {
 								uint64_t key = ((uint64_t)func_id << 32) | (uint64_t)arg_idx;
 								call_combined_args.insert(key, arg_id);
 							}
 						}
+						all_calls.push_back(rec);
 					}
 				} break;
 
@@ -1024,6 +1037,46 @@
 		}
 	}
 
+	// Transitively propagate the split through call chains. The pass above only
+	// catches a function called with a combined GLOBAL variable. But a wrapper
+	// can receive a combined sampler as a parameter and forward it to a deeper
+	// helper (tonemap's bicubic path does exactly this: main -> wrapper(global
+	// var) -> texture2D_bicubic(wrapper's param)). Every deeper helper must ALSO
+	// be split, with its parameter mapped back to the SAME underlying global var
+	// so the sampler load inside it resolves to that global's sampler. Iterate to
+	// a fixpoint so wrapper chains of any depth are fully covered. Without this a
+	// split param (ptr(Image)) is passed to an unsplit param (ptr(SampledImage)),
+	// producing invalid SPIR-V (OpFunctionCall argument type mismatch).
+	bool propagated = true;
+	while (propagated) {
+		propagated = false;
+		for (const CallRecord &rec : all_calls) {
+			const Vector<uint32_t> *params = function_param_ids.getptr(rec.func_id);
+			for (int i = 0; i < rec.args.size(); i++) {
+				// Underlying global combined var carried by this argument, if any.
+				uint32_t global_var = 0;
+				if (combined_vars.has(rec.args[i])) {
+					global_var = rec.args[i];
+				} else if (const uint32_t *v = param_combined.getptr(rec.args[i])) {
+					global_var = *v;
+				} else {
+					continue;
+				}
+				uint64_t key = ((uint64_t)rec.func_id << 32) | (uint64_t)i;
+				if (!call_combined_args.has(key)) {
+					call_combined_args.insert(key, global_var);
+				}
+				if (params && i < params->size()) {
+					uint32_t param_id = (*params)[i];
+					if (!param_combined.has(param_id)) {
+						param_combined.insert(param_id, global_var);
+						propagated = true;
+					}
+				}
+			}
+		}
+	}
+
 	// Build: func_id -> new_func_type_id for functions with combined-var params.
 	// Also build: param_id -> image_ptr_type_id for parameter type rewriting.
 	HashMap<uint32_t, uint32_t> param_new_type; // param_id -> new pointer type (image_ptr_type_id)
